00:03:07.730 --> 00:03:09.030
Yes.

00:03:09.030 --> 00:03:10.330
&gt;&gt; Leonard Bernstein: Terrific.

00:03:10.330 --> 00:03:11.630
Thank you.

00:03:11.630 --> 00:03:14.080
After reading your book, I
guess, the question I most want

00:03:14.080 --> 00:03:18.510
to know is why this
book at this time?

00:03:18.510 --> 00:03:19.810
&gt;&gt; Dr. Peter D. Kramer: Yes.

00:03:19.810 --> 00:03:21.240
&gt;&gt; Leonard Bernstein: Twenty three
years after your best seller.

00:03:21.240 --> 00:03:22.540
&gt;&gt; Dr. Peter D. Kramer: Right.

00:03:22.540 --> 00:03:24.530
&gt;&gt; Leonard Bernstein: Right at
time when one of eight people

00:03:24.530 --> 00:03:26.650 position:56%
in America is using antidepressants.

00:03:26.650 --> 00:03:27.950
&gt;&gt; Peter Kramer: Right.

00:03:27.950 --> 00:03:32.470
&gt;&gt; Leonard Bernstein: Why a defense
of Prozac and antidepressants?

00:03:32.470 --> 00:03:37.430
&gt;&gt; Peter Kramer: Most of my books
come the way writers books do

00:03:37.430 --> 00:03:43.850
out of some, you know, inspiring
thoughts, something that just needs

00:03:43.850 --> 00:03:47.870
to be written that is
writerly, some observation

00:03:47.870 --> 00:03:50.830 position:56%
that needs exploring and amplifying.

00:03:50.830 --> 00:03:53.930
This really is a cause book.

00:03:53.930 --> 00:03:58.200
This is a book I felt had
to be written for the sake

00:03:58.200 --> 00:04:03.740
of the patients, which is not a
comfortable starting point for me,

00:04:03.740 --> 00:04:07.300
and maybe why it took me a little
longer than some of my other books.

00:04:07.300 --> 00:04:11.590
But I tell stories at the
beginning of the book about people

00:04:11.590 --> 00:04:16.830
who really need antidepressants,
who either have not been prescribed

00:04:16.830 --> 00:04:19.880
to them because their doctors
have doubts that have been aroused

00:04:19.880 --> 00:04:23.530
by what I think is
spurious research that claim

00:04:23.530 --> 00:04:27.050 position:56%
that these antidepressants and in a
minimal say a little what depression

00:04:27.050 --> 00:04:28.750
or antidepressants are.

00:04:28.750 --> 00:04:33.010
But spurious research had said that
these medicines are a little more

00:04:33.010 --> 00:04:35.310
than placebos with side effects.

00:04:35.310 --> 00:04:38.880
Or, who are doing well on
antidepressants in ways

00:04:38.880 --> 00:04:41.260
that are important and
are cast into doubt,

00:04:41.260 --> 00:04:43.270
"Should I continue
taking the medicine?

00:04:43.270 --> 00:04:44.740
Is it really a placebo?"

00:04:44.740 --> 00:04:47.950 position:56%
And I'm not, by the way, saying
that everyone who is depressed needs

00:04:47.950 --> 00:04:50.800
to be on antidepressant or
everyone who is doing well

00:04:50.800 --> 00:04:52.970
on antidepressants
needs to stay on it.

00:04:52.970 --> 00:04:54.700
Just that that first question,

00:04:54.700 --> 00:04:58.370
do they work at all,
really can be discarded.

00:04:58.370 --> 00:05:03.940
And I think both researchers and
the press and the media had thrown

00:05:03.940 --> 00:05:09.460
that into doubt in a way that
is dangerous to patients.

00:05:09.460 --> 00:05:11.400
&gt;&gt; Leonard Bernstein: But
as a psychiatrist, it's--

00:05:11.400 --> 00:05:12.700
&gt;&gt; Dr. Peter D. Kramer: Yes.

00:05:12.700 --> 00:05:14.000 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Leonard Bernsteain: -- it's
quite obvious, antidepressants work.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:15.300
&gt;&gt; Peter Kramer: Right.

00:05:15.300 --> 00:05:16.600
&gt;&gt; Leonard Bernsteain:
Has there-- How has the--

00:05:16.600 --> 00:05:18.420
How are those doubts been raised?

00:05:18.420 --> 00:05:23.790
&gt;&gt; Peter Kramer: So, of course,
doctors see these medicines work.

00:05:23.790 --> 00:05:26.810
And the doubt that has been raised
isn't whether people get better

00:05:26.810 --> 00:05:30.460
on antidepressants, but
whether they get better based

00:05:30.460 --> 00:05:33.150
on the inherent efficacy
of the medicine.

00:05:33.150 --> 00:05:35.430
That is you could get better
just because of your faith

00:05:35.430 --> 00:05:38.750
from the doctor and your faith
in pills or you could better

00:05:38.750 --> 00:05:40.170 position:56%
because these medicines really work.

00:05:40.170 --> 00:05:42.620
That is the chemicals, they
are taken into your brain

00:05:42.620 --> 00:05:47.010
and they do something that's useful
for people with mood disorders.

00:05:47.010 --> 00:05:50.980
So, I want to just say, because
I have talked a lot to the public

00:05:50.980 --> 00:05:54.640
and I know that not everyone
knows this, what depression is?

00:05:54.640 --> 00:05:57.130
When we say depression,
what we're talking about?

00:05:57.130 --> 00:06:00.380
So, depression isn't
just ordinary sadness.

00:06:00.380 --> 00:06:01.680
It's a syndrome.

00:06:01.680 --> 00:06:03.350
It's a constellation of symptoms.

00:06:03.350 --> 00:06:06.840 position:56%
It's a disorder that's been
recognized, you know, since the time

00:06:06.840 --> 00:06:10.330
of your properties, starting
under the name, melancholia.

00:06:10.330 --> 00:06:13.740
And we-- And you know
it when you see it.

00:06:13.740 --> 00:06:15.820
Lately, it's been defined
by symptoms, right?

00:06:15.820 --> 00:06:17.620
So, people are sad.

00:06:17.620 --> 00:06:19.430
They can't experience pleasure.

00:06:19.430 --> 00:06:20.730
They're slowed down.

00:06:20.730 --> 00:06:22.030
They're apathetic.

00:06:22.030 --> 00:06:23.330
They may be suicidal.

00:06:23.330 --> 00:06:26.640
They may have problems with sleep
and appetite, low self-esteem.

00:06:26.640 --> 00:06:30.760
But it is those things
in a way that coheres

00:06:30.760 --> 00:06:33.720
and makes it hard to
function in life.

00:06:33.720 --> 00:06:36.080
And, you know, at the
extreme, you know,

00:06:36.080 --> 00:06:39.280
you can think about Picasso
paintings or Durer etchings

00:06:39.280 --> 00:06:42.880
where people are wringing their
hands and looking at the ground,

00:06:42.880 --> 00:06:47.100
and they're emaciated and almost
starving themselves to death,

00:06:47.100 --> 00:06:50.010 position:56%
and obsessed with negative thoughts.

00:06:50.010 --> 00:06:52.950
But there's a range of depressions.

00:06:52.950 --> 00:06:58.050
And some, which are, you know,
look or less recognizable

00:06:58.050 --> 00:07:01.230
in that way are still
very destructive in life.

00:07:01.230 --> 00:07:03.860
And I think when you're in the
presence of a depressed patient,

00:07:03.860 --> 00:07:08.300
you know pretty much what that
is, it's not ordinary sadness.

00:07:08.300 --> 00:07:10.610
And the antidepressants
are medicines

00:07:10.610 --> 00:07:14.340
that human kind has had access
to only for the last 60 years.

00:07:14.340 --> 00:07:17.350
Since Hippocrates,
doctors have wanted

00:07:17.350 --> 00:07:20.750
to have chemical approaches
to depression.

00:07:20.750 --> 00:07:23.900
The first antidepressants were
developed in the late 1950s.

00:07:23.900 --> 00:07:28.330
The concept that a
medicine would that we had

00:07:28.330 --> 00:07:32.590
to hand did this was really
elaborated in the 1950s.

00:07:32.590 --> 00:07:37.700
And then the way 1980s in Europe
and here, we have this newer group

00:07:37.700 --> 00:07:41.320
of antidepressants beginning with
Prozac and names that are familiar

00:07:41.320 --> 00:07:45.360
to you or things like Zoloft
and Celexa, Effexor or Lexapro.

00:07:45.360 --> 00:07:49.010
That's the class of
medicines we're talking about.

00:07:49.010 --> 00:07:50.310
&gt;&gt; Leonard Bernstein: Is it true

00:07:50.310 --> 00:07:52.070
that we still don't
really know how they work?

00:07:52.070 --> 00:07:53.370
&gt;&gt; Dr. Peter Kramer: It is true.

00:07:53.370 --> 00:07:54.950
&gt;&gt; Leonard Bernstein:
How can that be?

00:07:54.950 --> 00:07:59.390
&gt;&gt; Dr. Peter Kramer: Well,
the brain is very complicated.

00:07:59.390 --> 00:08:02.320
In "Listening to Prozac," I
quote a scientist who says,

00:08:02.320 --> 00:08:06.210 position:56%
"If the brain were simplest-- simple
enough for us to understand it,

00:08:06.210 --> 00:08:11.940
we would not be complex enough
to have that understanding."

00:08:11.940 --> 00:08:16.930
The-- We know a lot
of antidepressants.

00:08:16.930 --> 00:08:23.150
We know at the first level that
these medicines affect patterns

00:08:23.150 --> 00:08:24.590
of transmission in the brain,

00:08:24.590 --> 00:08:27.870
the way cells signal one
another with chemicals.

00:08:27.870 --> 00:08:33.810
And we know that these medicines
restore resilience in the brain

00:08:33.810 --> 00:08:36.350
in some quite general way.

00:08:36.350 --> 00:08:40.180 position:56%
So, they make it possible for people
to make new cells in the brain.

00:08:40.180 --> 00:08:43.790
Something we've only known
for about 20-25 years is

00:08:43.790 --> 00:08:47.200
that the adult human brain
continues to make new neurons

00:08:47.200 --> 00:08:49.280
in certain parts, and
they allow the brain

00:08:49.280 --> 00:08:51.480
to make new connections
between cells.

00:08:51.480 --> 00:08:54.250
And those things are
really muted in depression.

00:08:54.250 --> 00:08:58.590
Depression is a multisystem
illness that affects the brain,

00:08:58.590 --> 00:09:02.990
the brain's capacity to learn,
but it also affects bone,

00:09:02.990 --> 00:09:05.630
blood elements, hormonal glands.

00:09:05.630 --> 00:09:07.970
So, this is a body-wide disorder.

00:09:07.970 --> 00:09:11.800
But you know, at the core, we
have problems with the resilience

00:09:11.800 --> 00:09:14.180
in the brain and the
medicines restore that.

00:09:14.180 --> 00:09:17.050
I start the book with an
anecdote about a friend of mine

00:09:17.050 --> 00:09:20.540
who said we had a serious stroke,
and it turns out that this kind

00:09:20.540 --> 00:09:26.000
of stroke, there's more
recovery from this kind of stroke

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.140
if you're given antidepressants
early.

00:09:28.140 --> 00:09:30.010
Not because they fight depression

00:09:30.010 --> 00:09:33.930
but because they restore the
brain's ability apparently

00:09:33.930 --> 00:09:38.120
to elaborate the connections
between cells in this way.

00:09:38.120 --> 00:09:41.060
And this friend of
mine, his patient,

00:09:41.060 --> 00:09:44.180
was not getting antidepressants
because of this sort

00:09:44.180 --> 00:09:46.630
of created prejudice against them.

00:09:46.630 --> 00:09:50.100
And that really was the sort
of the trigger for my thinking

00:09:50.100 --> 00:09:53.120
about writing a book like this.

00:09:53.120 --> 00:09:54.730
&gt;&gt; Leonard Bernstein: So, we
don't know exactly how they work?

00:09:54.730 --> 00:09:56.030
&gt;&gt;Dr. Peter Kramer: Right.

00:09:56.030 --> 00:09:57.550
&gt;&gt; Leonard Bernstein:
But you as a psychiatrist

00:09:57.550 --> 00:09:59.570
and somewhat rare among
psychiatrists,

00:09:59.570 --> 00:10:03.390
you do both talk therapy
and prescribing--

00:10:03.390 --> 00:10:04.690
&gt;&gt; Dr. Peter Kramer: Right.

00:10:04.690 --> 00:10:05.990
&gt;&gt; Leonard Bernstein:
-- of antidepressants.

00:10:05.990 --> 00:10:09.360
So-- And you obviously see
that all of these works.

00:10:09.360 --> 00:10:10.660
&gt;&gt; Dr. Peter Kramer: Yes.

00:10:10.660 --> 00:10:13.370
&gt;&gt; Leonard Bernstein:
So, where on that scale

00:10:13.370 --> 00:10:16.380
between all medicine
and all talk therapy--

00:10:16.380 --> 00:10:17.680
&gt;&gt; Dr. Peter Kramer: Right.

00:10:17.680 --> 00:10:20.100
&gt;&gt; Leonard Bernstein: --
do you lie and how do--

00:10:20.100 --> 00:10:23.930
does the patient pick his
or her place on that--

00:10:23.930 --> 00:10:25.250
&gt;&gt; Dr. Peter Kramer: Right.

00:10:25.250 --> 00:10:30.320
So, it turns out that depression is
a relapsing and remitting disorder.

00:10:30.320 --> 00:10:32.060
It is chronic.

00:10:32.060 --> 00:10:35.000
People who've had a few
episodes are likely to have more.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:38.040
And that the later
episodes tend to be graver,

00:10:38.040 --> 00:10:41.530
they have more serious
symptoms, they last longer,

00:10:41.530 --> 00:10:45.230
they have more trouble responding
to whatever intervention we make.

00:10:45.230 --> 00:10:47.130 position:56%
So, we like to interrupt depression.

00:10:47.130 --> 00:10:51.570
And to me, the measure of worth
of a treatment in depression is

00:10:51.570 --> 00:10:56.110
that it works, so that the cases
made for exercise and meditation

00:10:56.110 --> 00:10:59.490
and yoga and a religious
counseling and so on.

00:10:59.490 --> 00:11:01.390
And the question is,
are you getting better?

00:11:01.390 --> 00:11:03.110
And if you're not getting better,

00:11:03.110 --> 00:11:06.700
the best tested remedies are
psychotherapy and medication.

00:11:06.700 --> 00:11:09.300
And my-- I usually
start talking to people.

00:11:09.300 --> 00:11:11.000
I want to know what's going on.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:15.340
And that in itself seems to
have some mitigating effect.

00:11:15.340 --> 00:11:17.240
And my measure as a doctor,

00:11:17.240 --> 00:11:20.600
and I think the doctor really is
the instrument here, is worry.

00:11:20.600 --> 00:11:24.110
If I start worrying that
this is really solid,

00:11:24.110 --> 00:11:27.390
that I'm not budging it, that
things are getting worse,

00:11:27.390 --> 00:11:30.740
we're falling behind,
I do tend to turn

00:11:30.740 --> 00:11:34.480 position:56%
to medication, and it tends to work.

00:11:34.480 --> 00:11:36.900
You know, there are-- You know,

00:11:36.900 --> 00:11:39.680
I don't know how well you
think these medicines work,

00:11:39.680 --> 00:11:43.140
there's a figure going around
that appears in the press lately.

00:11:43.140 --> 00:11:45.820
And part of this book is
quite critically depressed

00:11:45.820 --> 00:11:50.000
in how they look at research.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:53.980
But the figure is 30%, that
antidepressants help 30% of people.

00:11:53.980 --> 00:11:58.310
With that number which is wrong
in three ways comes from a study,

00:11:58.310 --> 00:12:01.620
very terrific study,
sponsored by the NIMH,

00:12:01.620 --> 00:12:05.700
the Institute of Mental
Health that looked at people

00:12:05.700 --> 00:12:11.390
who had been depressed, on average,
for 15 years, were in the seventh

00:12:11.390 --> 00:12:13.430
or eight episode of depression.

00:12:13.430 --> 00:12:16.590
That episode had lasted two years.

00:12:16.590 --> 00:12:20.620
Most of the patients in
addition were alcoholic

00:12:20.620 --> 00:12:22.400
or had a second mental illness.

00:12:22.400 --> 00:12:26.050
And in those patients, the
first antidepressant tried

00:12:26.050 --> 00:12:30.840
at ordinary doses caused
a remission.

00:12:30.840 --> 00:12:35.110
That is the episode of
depression ended in 30%.

00:12:35.110 --> 00:12:39.080 position:56%
To me, that's actually
astonishingly good figure, you know,

00:12:39.080 --> 00:12:42.260
why hadn't those patients
gotten better already.

00:12:42.260 --> 00:12:45.420
Half of them lost half
their symptoms.

00:12:45.420 --> 00:12:50.860
If you look in an unselected
population, primary care doctors,

00:12:50.860 --> 00:12:54.480
patients coming in, you see
much higher levels of response.

00:12:54.480 --> 00:12:57.770
So, we're not really discussing,
do people get better on this.

00:12:57.770 --> 00:12:59.100
There was a Swedish study looking

00:12:59.100 --> 00:13:02.790
at primary care populations,
nonsuicidal people.

00:13:02.790 --> 00:13:07.660
And by six months, 90% of them had
lost half their first symptoms.

00:13:07.660 --> 00:13:10.850
So, you know, people are very
responsive to these medicines.

00:13:10.850 --> 00:13:13.960
And the controversy that the
book is about is this question

00:13:13.960 --> 00:13:18.180
about whether depression is also
very responsive to placebo pills.

00:13:18.180 --> 00:13:21.680
I think it's not but it's
kind of a complicated story.

00:13:21.680 --> 00:13:25.980
And I try to tell it complexly
through stories from my practice,

00:13:25.980 --> 00:13:28.410
stories about the history
of psychiatry,

00:13:28.410 --> 00:13:33.710
and also some introduction to sort
of basic statistical approaches

00:13:33.710 --> 00:13:35.900
to research, how do
we measure depression,

00:13:35.900 --> 00:13:38.570
how do we measure change,
how do we combine studies,

00:13:38.570 --> 00:13:40.850
what makes this thing sort of--

00:13:40.850 --> 00:13:44.630
a medicine is working and how do
doctors outside psychiatry treating

00:13:44.630 --> 00:13:49.190
things like diabetes and asthma and
so on think about their treatments,

00:13:49.190 --> 00:13:50.490
you know, how do we compare.

00:13:50.490 --> 00:13:51.790
&gt;&gt; Leonard Bernstein: So,
at the risk of asking you

00:13:51.790 --> 00:13:53.350
to boil down your entire book--

00:13:53.350 --> 00:13:54.650
&gt;&gt; Dr. Peter Kramer: Right.

00:13:54.650 --> 00:13:57.850 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Leonard Bernstein: -- why doesn't
the placebo hypothesis worked up?

00:13:57.850 --> 00:14:00.150
&gt;&gt; Dr. Peter Kramer: Well, placebo
is very complicated, you know,

00:14:00.150 --> 00:14:05.130
you go into a study and all
sorts of things happen, right?

00:14:05.130 --> 00:14:09.280
You get a lot of attention from
doctors, time passes, you know,

00:14:09.280 --> 00:14:11.810
you return to employment
whatever it is.

00:14:11.810 --> 00:14:18.500
So, you need to say, what would
happen if we hadn't given the pill.

00:14:18.500 --> 00:14:21.780
