is most relevant, you know.

00:26:59.040 --> 00:27:03.380
That this was not really--
that depression, he said,

00:27:03.380 --> 00:27:06.640
is wimp of a word, you don't
understand what it was he was

00:27:06.640 --> 00:27:07.940
going through.

00:27:07.940 --> 00:27:11.070
But it really is the case that
these medicines were not used,

00:27:11.070 --> 00:27:14.810
on a principle basis, were
not used until after that.

00:27:14.810 --> 00:27:18.720
And in a way, well, after that,
they weren't used regularly even

00:27:18.720 --> 00:27:20.340
for very severe depression.

00:27:20.340 --> 00:27:24.390
So, it is that kind of story that
motivates the book that worries

00:27:24.390 --> 00:27:28.430
over that sort of dismissal
of these medicines.

00:27:28.430 --> 00:27:32.230 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Leonard Bernstein: I bet people
are ready to ask you some questions.

00:27:32.230 --> 00:27:37.170
Is there anybody who
would like to ask?

00:27:44.440 --> 00:27:47.020
&gt;&gt; Dr. Kramer, I have
a question about people

00:27:47.020 --> 00:27:52.180
who don't respond very well
to-- at-- to the initial--

00:27:52.180 --> 00:27:53.480
&gt;&gt; Dr. Peter Kramer: Right.

00:27:53.480 --> 00:27:55.650
&gt;&gt; -- medication that's
prescribed and maybe to try two

00:27:55.650 --> 00:27:59.340
or three different ones and maybe
other certain group of people

00:27:59.340 --> 00:28:01.950
who don't seem to respond
to any of them.

00:28:01.950 --> 00:28:05.200
I was just wondering, is
there something that you see

00:28:05.200 --> 00:28:09.730
that these non-responders have
in common or someway to kind

00:28:09.730 --> 00:28:16.470
of understand how to perceive with
people that have that presentation?

00:28:16.470 --> 00:28:17.770
&gt;&gt; Dr. Peter Kramer: Right.

00:28:17.770 --> 00:28:19.930
So, the question is
about non-responders.

00:28:19.930 --> 00:28:24.410
And, you know, sadly, there are
people who don't respond at all.

00:28:24.410 --> 00:28:29.450
And we have enormous need for-- to
anything that is the psychotherapy,

00:28:29.450 --> 00:28:32.600
medicines, combinations
of medication.

00:28:32.600 --> 00:28:37.010
There're few but they're-- but
because the disorder is so common,

00:28:37.010 --> 00:28:40.730
there're many of them if you
want on a percentage basis.

00:28:40.730 --> 00:28:46.410 position:56%
And, you know, sadly, for all sorts
of reasons, big pharma has retreated

00:28:46.410 --> 00:28:49.390
from development of drugs
in mental health altogether.

00:28:49.390 --> 00:28:52.520
And in the book, I write about
lots of promising avenues.

00:28:52.520 --> 00:28:56.270
I mentioned really lots of
promising avenues for research.

00:28:56.270 --> 00:29:00.120
But it's sort of mom-and-pop
garage band, sort of a research

00:29:00.120 --> 00:29:03.730
where small companies
try to get this attention

00:29:03.730 --> 00:29:05.770
to these potential remedies.

00:29:05.770 --> 00:29:08.350
And, of course, lots of
them fall by the wayside.

00:29:08.350 --> 00:29:12.720
But there isn't really the--
aren't really the resources devoted

00:29:12.720 --> 00:29:14.480
to this problem that
there should be.

00:29:14.480 --> 00:29:18.370
That said, I do also write
about some interesting studies

00:29:18.370 --> 00:29:20.580
that I think the press
has undercovered.

00:29:20.580 --> 00:29:25.000
And one of them was done by a
consortium of universities, Rush,

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:27.230
University of Pennsylvania,
Vanderbilt.

00:29:27.230 --> 00:29:31.070
And what they did was really
interesting, they took patients

00:29:31.070 --> 00:29:33.300
and they allowed the patients
in the study I mentioned,

00:29:33.300 --> 00:29:36.970
fairly chronic patients well
along in the course of depression,

00:29:36.970 --> 00:29:40.630
and they said to pharmacologists,
do your worst, you know,

00:29:40.630 --> 00:29:44.180 position:56%
this is not normally what's
studied, this was a pragmatic study,

00:29:44.180 --> 00:29:45.990
you couldn't have placebos
on the other side,

00:29:45.990 --> 00:29:47.770
there was nothing comparable.

00:29:47.770 --> 00:29:50.510
They just said, raise the dose
of the medicine, if you want,

00:29:50.510 --> 00:29:54.070
change it, add a second
medicine, add a third medicine.

00:29:54.070 --> 00:29:58.640
And half of the patients also were
given very intensive psychotherapy.

00:29:58.640 --> 00:30:01.090
And although the press
report of the opposite,

00:30:01.090 --> 00:30:05.530 position:56%
the truce was that you didn't see a
lot of effect from the psychotherapy

00:30:05.530 --> 00:30:07.070
because the medicine did so well.

00:30:07.070 --> 00:30:10.580
It turns out that if you
let doctors, skilled doctors

00:30:10.580 --> 00:30:14.110
and they were these kind of senior
advisors for the junior doctors

00:30:14.110 --> 00:30:19.000
in the study really try to
treat depression assertively,

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:23.130
you get most people to respond and
you get most of them to stay well

00:30:23.130 --> 00:30:26.170
for the length of time that they
looked which was six months.

00:30:26.170 --> 00:30:29.660
But it took some people
18 months to get better.

00:30:29.660 --> 00:30:34.080
So, this wasn't, you know,
kind of an easy process.

00:30:34.080 --> 00:30:36.280
And, of course, it is also
possible since they were--

00:30:36.280 --> 00:30:39.740
it wasn't comparison
group that in 18 months,

00:30:39.740 --> 00:30:41.660
a lot of people get
better on their own.

00:30:41.660 --> 00:30:44.340
But this wasn't a very
chronic group that hadn't--

00:30:44.340 --> 00:30:47.200
on the whole, the patients hadn't
gotten better on their own.

00:30:47.200 --> 00:30:50.930
So, I think one lesson from that
and as I say, it's upsetting to me

00:30:50.930 --> 00:30:55.210
that I think the press really is
happier to cover debunking stories

00:30:55.210 --> 00:30:58.560
that there have been, you know,
errors in assessing these medicines

00:30:58.560 --> 00:30:59.880
so they don't really work.

00:30:59.880 --> 00:31:02.850
But the studies in which they
are showing to work tend not

00:31:02.850 --> 00:31:04.700
to get the covers that they should.

00:31:04.700 --> 00:31:07.420
And it turns out most
people, if they--

00:31:07.420 --> 00:31:10.410
almost everyone is stuck with
the program, and of course,

00:31:10.410 --> 00:31:11.710
disappointed, people drop out.

00:31:11.710 --> 00:31:15.020
But almost everyone who sticks with
the program really does do better

00:31:15.020 --> 00:31:19.030
and manage to stay outside
of depression for a while.

00:31:19.030 --> 00:31:24.030
And even those people who didn't
do well on the whole didn't return

00:31:24.030 --> 00:31:25.330
to their baseline of depression,

00:31:25.330 --> 00:31:29.350
it's just that they started
accumulating some symptoms again.

00:31:29.350 --> 00:31:34.800
So, I think things are more
hopeful maybe than we imagine.

00:31:34.800 --> 00:31:37.580
&gt;&gt; Leonard Bernstein: Do
we have someone over here?

00:31:37.580 --> 00:31:41.600
&gt;&gt; Yes. Couldn't you preface
