00:31:49.970 --> 00:31:51.270
&gt;&gt; Dr. Peter Kramer: Oh yes.

00:31:51.270 --> 00:31:54.050
You know, should people be
well evaluated before medicines

00:31:54.050 --> 00:31:55.350
are prescribed?

00:31:55.350 --> 00:31:57.220
And, you know, my own
practice isn't just an hour.

00:31:57.220 --> 00:31:59.820
I may be with people
for an hour a week

00:31:59.820 --> 00:32:01.900
after week before we
decide to give a medicine.

00:32:01.900 --> 00:32:04.560
We may know each other pretty well.

00:32:04.560 --> 00:32:07.930
But, you know, lots of
things cause depression.

00:32:07.930 --> 00:32:11.660
Early in this book, I read
about someone who has a disorder

00:32:11.660 --> 00:32:14.250
of the hormonal gland,
thyroid disorder.

00:32:14.250 --> 00:32:17.720
And the question is whether
that's causing the depression.

00:32:17.720 --> 00:32:21.020
So, you need, you know, a good
evaluation that involves maybe

00:32:21.020 --> 00:32:24.540
in addition to-- interviewed--
in the course of the interview,

00:32:24.540 --> 00:32:26.630
you may decide you ought
to be giving blood tests

00:32:26.630 --> 00:32:29.420
and taking blood tests,
evaluating people.

00:32:29.420 --> 00:32:33.800
People really-- You know, this,
when we take the perspective

00:32:33.800 --> 00:32:35.140
that this is a medical disorder

00:32:35.140 --> 00:32:38.300
which of course isn't the only
perspective on depression,

00:32:38.300 --> 00:32:42.250
"Against Depression," the
earlier book of mine from 2005 is

00:32:42.250 --> 00:32:45.420
about how we conceptualize
depression altogether.

00:32:45.420 --> 00:32:47.780
But if we take it as a medical
disorder, we really have

00:32:47.780 --> 00:32:51.290
to evaluate it as a
medical disorder.

00:32:51.290 --> 00:32:54.190
That said, I'm not
one of these people

00:32:54.190 --> 00:32:57.450
who think primary care
doctors do so badly with this.

00:32:57.450 --> 00:33:01.440 position:56%
There has been an enormous effort
on the part of governmental agencies

00:33:01.440 --> 00:33:06.860
and nonprofits to make general
doctors aware of depression.

00:33:06.860 --> 00:33:08.550
I think they're better
at assessing it,

00:33:08.550 --> 00:33:10.500
they're better at recognizing it.

00:33:10.500 --> 00:33:14.260
And that although we worry about
the overuse of this medicine,

00:33:14.260 --> 00:33:17.990
on the whole, the fact that
depression is getting recognized

00:33:17.990 --> 00:33:21.020
and treated is probably
for the good.

00:33:21.020 --> 00:33:25.310
And I certainly find people coming
to me who've only been treated say

00:33:25.310 --> 00:33:29.340
by a gynecologist or whatever who
come in and they said, you know,

00:33:29.340 --> 00:33:31.860
it's not just that I'm a
little better on this medicine,

00:33:31.860 --> 00:33:33.720
it's that I see my
marriage differently.

00:33:33.720 --> 00:33:37.600
I see that it wasn't all my wife
that I had some contribution

00:33:37.600 --> 00:33:40.660
that there's some loosening up
of perspective as takes place

00:33:40.660 --> 00:33:45.070
in psychotherapy sometimes in
a good response to medication.

00:33:45.070 --> 00:33:52.440
So, I'm kind of on the optimistic
side about a broader group

00:33:52.440 --> 00:33:54.980
of doctors using these medicines

00:33:54.980 --> 00:33:57.870
because we simply don't
have that many specialists.

00:33:57.870 --> 00:33:59.170
&gt;&gt; Leonard Bernstein: Sir?

00:33:59.170 --> 00:34:03.560
&gt;&gt; Yeah. I'd really be
