00:39:52.040 --> 00:39:54.650
or seen inadequate in some way.

00:39:54.650 --> 00:39:59.670
And I wonder if maybe the situation
is that it's very difficult

00:39:59.670 --> 00:40:02.090
or it's often done
poorly or inadequately.

00:40:02.090 --> 00:40:07.640
And it's still important to
understand oneself and people

00:40:07.640 --> 00:40:09.790
in at least a theoretical way.

00:40:09.790 --> 00:40:11.090
&gt;&gt; Dr. Peter Kramer: Right.

00:40:11.090 --> 00:40:13.560
So, I want to extend this question

00:40:13.560 --> 00:40:16.630
about whether psychotherapy
is always done well

00:40:16.630 --> 00:40:21.730
and whether people not doing well
in psychotherapy is effective,

00:40:21.730 --> 00:40:25.040
the expertise say or the match
between doctor and patient rather

00:40:25.040 --> 00:40:28.990
than inherently psychotherapy not
having a potential be effective

00:40:28.990 --> 00:40:30.300
for that patient.

00:40:30.300 --> 00:40:33.560
And I want to take this on a
little slightly different direction

00:40:33.560 --> 00:40:37.140
which is really antidepressants
have been well tested.

00:40:37.140 --> 00:40:40.400
And if these complicated critics
where they say well, you know,

00:40:40.400 --> 00:40:43.460
maybe some studies haven't
been published and we can look

00:40:43.460 --> 00:40:46.430
at the data and see a
pattern that says that

00:40:46.430 --> 00:40:49.390
and if we imagine we had
all the studies, they,

00:40:49.390 --> 00:40:51.640
which are themselves
to be less effective.

00:40:51.640 --> 00:40:56.010
And even under those conditions,
antidepressants look effective.

00:40:56.010 --> 00:41:00.600
But psychotherapy, when it's put to
the same test, really does poorly.

00:41:00.600 --> 00:41:04.440
It does seem to be the case that
when you study psychotherapy,

00:41:04.440 --> 00:41:06.410
when people have good results,
they like to publish them,

00:41:06.410 --> 00:41:08.600
when they have bad results,
they don't like to publish them.

00:41:08.600 --> 00:41:12.020
So, you get a very
distorted literature.

00:41:12.020 --> 00:41:15.780
That said, it's really
hard to test psychotherapy.

00:41:15.780 --> 00:41:19.080
You don't know whether the doctors
are well trained and you don't have

00:41:19.080 --> 00:41:22.580
that advantage of people saying,
I don't just like this therapist,

00:41:22.580 --> 00:41:23.980
I'm going to a different one.

00:41:23.980 --> 00:41:26.670 position:56%
You know, in this study, you're kind
of stuck with the person you have.

00:41:26.670 --> 00:41:28.560
It's free, you're glad
to have it, you know,

00:41:28.560 --> 00:41:31.370
but it's maybe not the
person you would have chosen.

00:41:31.370 --> 00:41:34.170
And maybe it's not that taking
[inaudible] psychotherapy is going

00:41:34.170 --> 00:41:35.470
to work best for you.

00:41:35.470 --> 00:41:39.960
So, I think that research really
under measures the efficacy

00:41:39.960 --> 00:41:43.010
of psychotherapy which I
find, you know, in my practice

00:41:43.010 --> 00:41:47.620
to be extremely useful and
really, sustaining for people even

00:41:47.620 --> 00:41:51.000
where they do labs back
into anxiety or depression

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:53.780
that the psychotherapy
seems to be helpful

00:41:53.780 --> 00:41:58.250
in keeping them afloat while they
have a return of some symptoms.

00:41:58.250 --> 00:41:59.910
So, I'm a big fan of psychotherapy.

00:41:59.910 --> 00:42:06.820
And I do think it is, you
know, very hard to measure.

00:42:06.820 --> 00:42:09.460
Lots of things in medicine
are hard to measure.

00:42:09.460 --> 00:42:13.220
I mean, I hope this book is
amusing as well as serious.

00:42:13.220 --> 00:42:16.490
And there are some
amusing things that happen,

00:42:16.490 --> 00:42:18.810
you won't find this amusing,
but there was a study

00:42:18.810 --> 00:42:21.060
of these surgical checklists,
you know,

00:42:21.060 --> 00:42:26.350 position:56%
where you catechize the doctors and
make sure they got all these sponges

00:42:26.350 --> 00:42:29.860
out of the patient before they
close them up that, you know,

00:42:29.860 --> 00:42:33.830
there were these analyses that
combined lots of small studies

00:42:33.830 --> 00:42:37.420
and showed that 60%
fewer patients died

00:42:37.420 --> 00:42:39.390
when you're at surgical checklist.

00:42:39.390 --> 00:42:43.150
And then finally, when they
did a large study in Canada,

00:42:43.150 --> 00:42:45.690
they required everyone in
Toronto to use the checklist,

00:42:45.690 --> 00:42:48.760
and the researchers were able
to look at what happened before

00:42:48.760 --> 00:42:50.540
and after the checklist
were introduced,

00:42:50.540 --> 00:42:52.220
there was no difference at all.

00:42:52.220 --> 00:42:55.360
And probably, the story
was, you know, first of all,

00:42:55.360 --> 00:42:59.780
maybe they were adopted more
willingly in other places

00:42:59.780 --> 00:43:02.950
and maybe they're being forced to
adopt and it wasn't as helpful.

00:43:02.950 --> 00:43:06.600
But mainly, hospital systems
that introduced new methods

00:43:06.600 --> 00:43:10.280
and had more people die
didn't publish the articles.

00:43:10.280 --> 00:43:14.280
So, you had, you know, an
enormous bias in the literature.

00:43:14.280 --> 00:43:19.240
And, you know, I think in
general, I hope in this book,

00:43:19.240 --> 00:43:20.810
I'm educating people about how

00:43:20.810 --> 00:43:24.930
to read not just technical
scientific articles but articles

00:43:24.930 --> 00:43:27.340
in the Washington Post, the
New York Times and, you know,

00:43:27.340 --> 00:43:30.160
online and all the things
that pass through your Twitter

00:43:30.160 --> 00:43:34.750
and Facebook feeds, how to
read them skeptically and think

00:43:34.750 --> 00:43:36.460
if this study had come
out differently,

00:43:36.460 --> 00:43:38.290 position:56%
would it have been published at all.

00:43:38.290 --> 00:43:40.320
So, yes.

